Data Analysis¶

Data input¶

Most regression lines shown in this notebook are made using lowess regression, which might be seen as a locally weighted linear regession. [1]

[1] - Cleveland, W.S. (1979) “Robust Locally Weighted Regression and Smoothing Scatterplots”. Journal of the American Statistical Association 74 (368): 829-836.

"Fitness landscape"¶

The figures below show the fitness landscape, the impact of a certain variable on the number of children an individual has, and how that variable shifts over time.

def cor(df, col_name, points=50, ax=None):
    if not ax:
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1)
    plt.sca(ax)
    corrs = []
    min = df.birthtime.min()
    max = df.birthtime.max()
    c = (max-min)/points
    for i in range(points):
        df_ind = df[(df.birthtime >= i*c) & (df.birthtime < (i+1)*c)][
            ['numberOfChildren', col_name]].corr(method='kendall')[['numberOfChildren']]
        corrs += [df_ind.loc[col_name,'numberOfChildren']]
    
    sns.regplot(x=np.array(range(points)), y=np.array(corrs), label=col_name, lowess=True, scatter_kws = {'s':1})
    plt.ylim([-0.05, 0.3])
    #plt.title('Correlation with number of children')
    plt.legend()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize=(16,20))
for i, c in enumerate(cost_order):
    d = df_all_cost[df_all_cost.cost == c]
    for ds in ds_order:
        temp_d = d[d.DiseaseStrength == ds]
        if temp_d.empty:
            continue
        sns.distplot(temp_d.birthtime.dropna(), ax=ax[i//2][i%2], label=ds, bins=15)
    plt.sca(ax[i//2][i%2])
    plt.title(c)
    plt.ylim((0,0.035))
    plt.legend()
